                {
                    "id": "eq26_positivity_extreme_fast",
                    "description": "Extreme-fast end of the upstream `3.1 Lifetime Positivity` sweep (atmospheric_lifetime_test.jl:300-319): override lambda to 1.0 s^-1. The first-order lifetime tau_first_order = 1/lambda = 1.0 s is positive and finite, as the upstream test asserts. Anchors the short-lived extreme of Eq. 2.6; together with `eq26_positivity_extreme_slow` it pins the two endpoints of the upstream positivity sweep, spanning ten orders of magnitude in lifetime.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {"lambda": 1.0},
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "tau_first_order", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1.0}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "eq26_methane_effective_oh_rate",
                    "description": "Real-species anchor for Eq. 2.6: methane (CH4) removed by reaction with the tropospheric OH radical. The effective first-order rate constant is lambda = k_OH*[OH] = 6.3e-15 cm^3/(molec*s) * 1.0e6 molec/cm^3 = 6.3e-9 s^-1, using the JPL-evaluation rate constant and the global-mean OH concentration of the upstream test `2.9 Eq. 2.12` and the docs `OH Reaction Lifetimes` figure. The first-order lifetime tau_first_order = 1/lambda = 1.5873015873015872e8 s ≈ 5.0 years reproduces the canonical ~5-year OH-oxidation lifetime of methane (the upstream OHReactionLifetime test `2.9` asserts ~5 years at rtol=0.1). Demonstrates that Eq. 2.6 applied with an OH effective rate constant yields the OH-reaction lifetime of Eq. 2.12.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {"lambda": 6.3e-9},
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "tau_first_order", "time": 0.0, "expected": 158730158.73015872},
                        {"variable": "tau_removal", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1000000.0}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "eq26_carbon_monoxide_effective_oh_rate",
                    "description": "Real-species anchor for Eq. 2.6: carbon monoxide (CO) removed by reaction with the tropospheric OH radical. The effective first-order rate constant is lambda = k_OH*[OH] = 2.4e-13 cm^3/(molec*s) * 1.0e6 molec/cm^3 = 2.4e-7 s^-1, using the rate constant and global-mean OH concentration of the upstream test `2.9 Eq. 2.12`. The first-order lifetime tau_first_order = 1/lambda = 4166666.666666667 s ≈ 48 days reproduces the canonical ~48-day OH-oxidation lifetime of CO (the upstream test `2.9` asserts ~48 days at rtol=0.1). With CH4 (~5 years) and CO (~48 days) the two real-species tests span the long-lived to intermediate range of tropospheric OH-controlled lifetimes.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {"lambda": 2.4e-7},
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "tau_first_order", "time": 0.0, "expected": 4166666.666666667}
                    ]
                }
            ],
            "examples": [
                {
                    "id": "first_order_lifetime_spectrum",
                    "description": "Sweep the first-order removal rate constant lambda across five orders of magnitude (1.0e-9 to 1.0e-4 s^-1, logarithmically) with all other parameters at their defaults, plotting the first-order atmospheric lifetime tau_first_order = 1/lambda (S&P Eq. 2.6). The canonical inverse relationship: on log-log axes an exact straight line of slope -1. The swept range spans the realistic atmospheric trace-species lifetime spectrum, from tau ≈ 1.0e9 s (~32 years, very-long-lived gases) at lambda=1.0e-9 down to tau ≈ 1.0e4 s (~2.8 hours, short-lived reactive species) at lambda=1.0e-4 — the full dynamic range over which Eq. 2.6 is applied in atmospheric chemistry.",
                    "initial_state": {"type": "per_variable", "values": {}},
                    "parameters": {},
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "lambda",
                                "range": {"start": 1.0e-9, "stop": 1.0e-4, "count": 60, "scale": "log"}
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "tau_first_order_vs_lambda_loglog",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "First-order atmospheric lifetime tau_first_order as a function of the removal rate constant lambda, on log-log axes — an exact straight line of slope -1 because tau_first_order = 1/lambda means log(tau) = -log(lambda). At lambda=1.0e-9 s^-1, tau ≈ 32 years; at lambda=1.0e-6 s^-1 (the default), tau ≈ 11.6 days; at lambda=1.0e-4 s^-1, tau ≈ 2.8 hours. The shape verifies the canonical inverse-rate-constant scaling of S&P Eq. 2.6.",
                            "x": {"variable": "lambda", "label": "first-order removal rate constant lambda (s^-1)"},
                            "y": {"variable": "tau_first_order", "label": "first-order lifetime tau_first_order (s)"}
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "general_lifetime_vs_outflow",
                    "description": "Sweep the outflow rate F_out from 0 (no transport out of the reservoir) to 1.0e7 mol/s (outflow ten times the default chemical removal rate R_removal) with all other parameters at their defaults, plotting the general atmospheric lifetime tau_general = Q/(R_removal + F_out) (S&P Eq. 2.3). At F_out=0 the general lifetime equals the removal-only lifetime tau_removal = Q/R_removal = 1.0e6 s (Eq. 2.4, the global-atmosphere limit); as F_out grows, the added loss channel monotonically shortens the lifetime, asymptoting to the outflow-dominated limit Q/F_out. Surfaces how physical transport out of a reservoir competes with in-place chemical removal.",
                    "initial_state": {"type": "per_variable", "values": {}},
                    "parameters": {},
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "F_out",
                                "range": {"start": 0.0, "stop": 1.0e7, "count": 50, "scale": "linear"}
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "tau_general_vs_F_out",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "General atmospheric lifetime tau_general as a function of the outflow rate F_out, on linear axes. Strictly decreasing from tau_general = 1.0e6 s at F_out=0 (where it equals the removal-only lifetime tau_removal) toward the outflow-dominated limit Q/F_out as F_out grows large. The curve is the rectangular hyperbola tau_general = Q/(R_removal + F_out).",
                            "x": {"variable": "F_out", "label": "outflow rate F_out (mol/s)"},
                            "y": {"variable": "tau_general", "label": "general lifetime tau_general (s)"}
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "removal_lifetime_vs_burden",
                    "description": "Sweep the species burden Q across four orders of magnitude (1.0e10 to 1.0e14 mol, logarithmically) with all other parameters at their defaults, plotting the removal-based lifetime tau_removal = Q/R_removal (S&P Eq. 2.4). The lifetime is exactly linear in the burden — on log-log axes a straight line of slope +1 — because for a fixed removal rate R_removal a larger reservoir takes proportionally longer to empty. Illustrates the burden-linearity shared by Eqs. 2.3-2.5, in contrast to the burden-independent first-order lifetime of Eq. 2.6.",
                    "initial_state": {"type": "per_variable", "values": {}},
                    "parameters": {},
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "Q",
                                "range": {"start": 1.0e10, "stop": 1.0e14, "count": 50, "scale": "log"}
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "tau_removal_vs_Q_loglog",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "Removal-based atmospheric lifetime tau_removal as a function of the species burden Q, on log-log axes — an exact straight line of slope +1 because tau_removal = Q/R_removal is linear in Q at fixed R_removal. At Q=1.0e10 mol, tau_removal = 1.0e4 s; at Q=1.0e12 mol (the default), tau_removal = 1.0e6 s; at Q=1.0e14 mol, tau_removal = 1.0e8 s.",
                            "x": {"variable": "Q", "label": "species burden Q (mol)"},
                            "y": {"variable": "tau_removal", "label": "removal lifetime tau_removal (s)"}
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "general_lifetime_loss_partition_heatmap",
                    "description": "Joint two-dimensional sweep of the chemical removal rate R_removal (1.0e5 to 1.0e7 mol/s, logarithmically) and the outflow rate F_out (1.0e4 to 1.0e6 mol/s, logarithmically) at the default burden Q=1.0e12 mol, surfacing the general atmospheric lifetime tau_general = Q/(R_removal + F_out) (S&P Eq. 2.3) as a function of its two competing loss channels. The lifetime is set by the total loss rate R_removal + F_out: longest in the low-R_removal / low-F_out corner (both channels weak), shortest in the high-R_removal / high-F_out corner (both strong). The iso-lifetime contours are lines of constant R_removal + F_out — the signature that chemical removal and physical outflow add as parallel sinks.",
                    "initial_state": {"type": "per_variable", "values": {}},
                    "parameters": {},
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "R_removal",
                                "range": {"start": 1.0e5, "stop": 1.0e7, "count": 25, "scale": "log"}
                            },
                            {
                                "parameter": "F_out",
                                "range": {"start": 1.0e4, "stop": 1.0e6, "count": 25, "scale": "log"}
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "tau_general_vs_R_removal_and_F_out",
                            "type": "heatmap",
                            "description": "General atmospheric lifetime tau_general over the (R_removal, F_out) plane on log-log axes. The color channel is tau_general = Q/(R_removal + F_out) at the default burden Q=1.0e12 mol; iso-lifetime contours are lines of constant total loss rate R_removal + F_out, running diagonally across the plane. The lifetime ranges from ~9.1e6 s in the weak-loss corner (R_removal=1.0e5, F_out=1.0e4) to ~9.1e4 s in the strong-loss corner (R_removal=1.0e7, F_out=1.0e6).",
                            "x": {"variable": "R_removal", "label": "chemical removal rate R_removal (mol/s)"},
                            "y": {"variable": "F_out", "label": "outflow rate F_out (mol/s)"},
                            "value": {"variable": "tau_general", "reduce": "final"}
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        }
    }
}
